Media Owner, Publisher and Distributor:
§ 1 Scope
1.1 These General Terms and Conditions for the hospitality industry (hereinafter “AGBH 2006”) replace the previous ÖHVB version of September 23, 1981.
1.2 The AGBH 2006 do not exclude special agreements. They apply subsidiarily to individually concluded agreements.
§ 2 Definitions
2.1 Definitions:
"Provider": A natural or legal person who provides accommodation for a fee.
"Guest": A natural person who uses the accommodation service. The guest is usually also the contracting party. Persons traveling with the contracting party (e.g. family members, friends, etc.) are likewise considered guests.
"Contracting Party": A natural or legal person from within or outside the country who enters into an accommodation contract as a guest or on behalf of a guest.
"Consumer" and "Entrepreneur": These terms are to be understood in accordance with the Consumer Protection Act of 1979 as amended.
"Accommodation Contract": The contract concluded between the provider and the contracting party, the content of which is subsequently regulated in detail.
§ 3 Conclusion of Contract – Deposit
3.1 The accommodation contract is concluded by the provider’s acceptance of the contracting party’s order. Electronic declarations are deemed received if the party for which they are intended can normally access them and if they are received during the provider’s stated business hours.
3.2 The provider is entitled to conclude the accommodation contract on the condition that the contracting party pays a deposit. In this case, the provider is obliged to inform the contracting party about the required deposit before accepting the order, whether in writing or orally. If the contracting party agrees to the deposit (in writing or orally), the accommodation contract is concluded upon receipt of the confirmation of deposit payment.
3.3 The contracting party must pay the deposit at least 7 days (in advance) before the accommodation. The contracting party bears the costs of the money transfer (e.g. bank transfer fees). The conditions of the respective credit or debit card companies apply.
3.4 The deposit is an advance payment toward the agreed fee.
§ 4 Start and End of Accommodation
4.1 Unless the provider offers an alternative check-in time, the contracting party has the right to check in to the rented rooms at 4:00 PM on the agreed day (“arrival day”).
4.2 If a room is used for the first time before 6:00 AM, the preceding night is counted as the first night.
4.3 The contracting party must vacate the rented rooms by 12:00 PM on the day of departure. The provider is entitled to charge for an additional day if the rooms are not vacated on time.
§ 5 Cancellation of the Accommodation Contract – Cancellation Fee
Cancellation by the Provider:
5.1 If the accommodation contract stipulates a deposit and the deposit is not paid on time, the provider may cancel the contract without further notice.
5.2 If the guest does not appear by 6:00 PM on the agreed arrival day, no accommodation obligation arises, unless a later arrival time has been agreed.
5.3 If the contracting party has paid a deposit (see 3.3), the rooms remain reserved until at least 12:00 PM on the day following the agreed stay. In cases of prepayment for more than four days, the accommodation obligation ends at 6:00 PM on the fourth day, with the arrival day counted as the first day, unless a later arrival day is notified.
5.4 Up to 3 months before the agreed arrival day, the provider may unilaterally cancel the contract for justified reasons.
Cancellation by the Contracting Party – Cancellation Fee:
5.5 Up to 3 months before the arrival day, the contracting party may cancel the contract unilaterally without incurring a cancellation fee.
5.6 Outside this period, unilateral cancellation by the contracting party is only possible subject to the following cancellation fees:
- Up to 1 month before the arrival day: 40% of the total arrangement price;
- Up to 1 week before the arrival day: 70% of the total arrangement price;
- In the last week before the arrival day: 90% of the total arrangement price.
Impairment of Arrival:
5.7 If the contracting party is unable to arrive at the accommodation on the day of arrival due to unforeseeable extraordinary circumstances (e.g. extreme snowfall, flooding, etc.) making all travel impossible, the contracting party is not obliged to pay the fee for the arrival day.
5.8 The payment obligation for the booked stay resumes once arrival is possible again within three days.
§ 6 Provision of an Alternative Accommodation
6.1 The provider may offer the contracting party or the guests an adequate alternative accommodation (of equal quality) if this is reasonable – particularly if the deviation is minor and objectively justified.
6.2 Objective justification exists, for example, if the room(s) become unusable, if already accommodated guests extend their stay, if there is an overbooking, or if other important operational measures require it.
6.3 Any additional expenses for the alternative accommodation are borne by the provider.
§ 7 Rights of the Contracting Party
7.1 By entering into an accommodation contract, the contracting party acquires the right to the usual use of the rented rooms, the generally accessible facilities of the accommodation establishment, and the standard service – in accordance with any applicable hotel and/or guest regulations (house rules).
§ 8 Obligations of the Contracting Party
8.1 The contracting party is obliged to pay the agreed fee, plus any additional charges arising from the use of special services by the contracting party and/or accompanying guests, plus statutory VAT, no later than at the time of departure.
8.2 The provider is not obliged to accept foreign currencies. If foreign currencies are accepted, they are converted at the prevailing rate. In this case, the contracting party bears all related costs (e.g. credit card fees, telegrams, etc.).
8.3 The contracting party is liable to the provider for any damage caused by him, the guest, or other persons who, with his knowledge or consent, utilize the provider’s services.
§ 9 Rights of the Provider
9.1 If the contracting party refuses to pay the agreed fee or is in arrears, the provider is entitled to exercise the statutory right of retention pursuant to § 970c ABGB as well as the statutory lien pursuant to § 1101 ABGB on the items provided by the contracting party or guest. This right serves to secure the provider’s claim arising from the accommodation contract, particularly for catering, other expenses incurred on behalf of the contracting party, and any compensation claims.
9.2 If room service or service at extraordinary times (after 8:00 PM and before 6:00 AM) is requested by the contracting party, the provider is entitled to charge an additional fee, which must be displayed on the room rate board. The provider may also refuse these services for operational reasons.
9.3 The provider has the right to settle accounts or issue interim invoices at any time.
§ 10 Obligations of the Provider
10.1 The provider is obliged to render the agreed services in accordance with its standard.
10.2 Additional services not included in the accommodation fee that can be charged separately include, for example:
   a) Additional accommodation services such as the provision of salons, sauna, indoor pool, swimming pool, solarium, garage, etc.;
   b) A reduced price is charged for the provision of extra or child beds.
§ 11 Liability of the Provider for Damage to Items Brought In
11.1 The provider is liable pursuant to §§ 970 ff. ABGB for the items brought in by the contracting party. Liability exists only if the items have been handed over to the provider or to persons authorized by the provider or have been taken to a designated storage location. Failing to prove otherwise, the provider is liable for his own fault, the fault of his personnel, and the fault of third parties. Liability under § 970 (1) ABGB is limited to the amount prescribed by the Federal Act of November 16, 1921 on the liability of restaurateurs and other entrepreneurs. If the contracting party or guest does not promptly comply with the provider’s request to deposit their items, the provider is released from liability. The maximum liability is limited to the provider’s liability insurance sum. Any fault on the part of the contracting party or guest is disregarded.
11.2 The provider’s liability for slight negligence is excluded. If the contracting party is an entrepreneur, liability for both slight and gross negligence is excluded. In this case, the burden of proof for fault lies with the contracting party. Consequential, indirect damages or lost profits will not be compensated.
11.3 The provider is only liable for valuables, money, and securities up to the amount of currently € 550,--. Liability beyond this amount exists only if the provider accepted the items for safekeeping with knowledge of their nature or if the damage was caused by him or his staff. The limitations in 12.1 and 12.2 apply accordingly.
11.4 The provider may refuse to store valuables, money, and securities if they exceed the usual amount kept by guests.
11.5 In all cases of safekeeping, liability is excluded if the contracting party or guest does not notify the provider of any damage immediately. Furthermore, claims must be brought to court within three years of becoming aware of the damage, otherwise the right expires.
§ 12 Limitation of Liability
12.1 If the contracting party is a consumer, the provider’s liability for slight negligence—except in cases of personal injury—is excluded.
12.2 If the contracting party is an entrepreneur, the provider’s liability for both slight and gross negligence is excluded. In this case, the burden of proof for fault lies with the contracting party. Consequential, immaterial or indirect damages as well as lost profits will not be compensated. The damage is in any event limited to the contractual interest.
§ 13 Pet Ownership
13.1 Animals may only be brought into the accommodation establishment with the provider’s prior consent and, if applicable, for an additional fee.
13.2 The contracting party who brings an animal is obliged to ensure that the animal is properly supervised during the stay or, at their own expense, have it supervised by a suitable third party.
13.3 The contracting party or guest who brings an animal must have appropriate pet liability or personal liability insurance that also covers damages caused by animals. Proof of such insurance must be provided upon request.
13.4 The contracting party or their insurer is jointly liable to the provider for any damage caused by the animal. This includes, in particular, any compensation the provider must pay to third parties.
13.5 Animals are not permitted in salons, social areas, restaurants, or wellness areas.
§ 14 Extension of the Accommodation
14.1 The contracting party has no right to extend the stay. If the contracting party notifies the provider of a wish to extend the stay in good time, the provider may agree to extend the accommodation contract but is under no obligation to do so.
14.2 If the contracting party is unable to leave the accommodation on the day of departure due to unforeseeable extraordinary circumstances (e.g. extreme snowfall, flooding, etc.) that render all departure options impossible, the accommodation contract is automatically extended for the duration of the departureunmöglichkeit. A fee reduction is only possible if the contracting party cannot fully utilize the offered services due to exceptional weather conditions. The provider is entitled to charge at least the rate usually applied in the off-season.
§ 15 Termination of the Accommodation Contract – Early Termination
15.1 If the accommodation contract was concluded for a fixed period, it ends with the expiration of that period.
15.2 If the contracting party departs early, the provider is entitled to charge the full agreed fee. Any savings resulting from non-utilization of services or from renting the rooms to other guests will be deducted. The burden of proof for such savings lies with the contracting party.
15.3 The contract terminates upon the death of a guest.
15.4 If the contract was concluded for an indefinite period, either party may terminate it by 10:00 AM on the third day prior to the intended termination.
15.5 The provider is entitled to terminate the contract with immediate effect for good cause, particularly if:
   a) the contracting party or guest uses the rooms in a significantly detrimental manner or behaves recklessly, offensively, or grossly inappropriately such that the coexistence of other guests, the owner, his staff, or other persons in the establishment is disturbed;
   b) the guest contracts a contagious disease or a disease that extends beyond the stay, or becomes in need of care;
   c) the presented invoices are not paid within a reasonable period (3 days).
15.6 If performance becomes impossible due to an event considered force majeure (e.g. natural disasters, strikes, lockouts, governmental orders, etc.), the provider may terminate the contract at any time without notice, provided the contract has not already been deemed terminated by law or the provider is released from his duty. Claims for damages by the contracting party are excluded.
§ 16 Illness or Death of the Guest
16.1 If a guest becomes ill during the stay, the provider will arrange for medical care at the guest’s request. In urgent cases, medical care will be arranged even without the guest’s express request, provided the guest is unable to decide for themselves.
16.2 As long as the guest is unable to make decisions or if the guest’s relatives cannot be contacted, the provider will arrange for medical treatment at the guest’s expense. This obligation ends once the guest regains decision-making capacity or the relatives have been informed.
16.3 The provider is entitled to claim reimbursement from the contracting party, the guest, or in the event of death, their legal successors, in particular for:
   a) Outstanding medical costs, costs for medical transport, medications, and therapies;
   b) Necessary room disinfection;
   c) Laundry, bed linen, and bedding that have become unusable or costs for disinfection/thorough cleaning thereof;
   d) Restoration of walls, furnishings, carpets, etc., insofar as these have become soiled or damaged in connection with the illness or death;
   e) Room rent for the period during which the guest occupied the room, plus any additional days of unavailability (e.g. due to disinfection);
   f) Any other damages incurred by the provider.
§ 17 Place of Performance, Jurisdiction, and Choice of Law
17.1 The place of performance is the location of the accommodation establishment.
17.2 This contract is governed by Austrian formal and substantive law under exclusion of the rules of private international law (in particular IPRG and EVÜ) as well as the UN Convention on Contracts for the International Sale of Goods.
17.3 The exclusive jurisdiction in commercial matters is the provider’s registered office, although the provider may assert its rights before any other locally and jurisdictionally competent court.
